{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332894195/1930021802/0321.xml":{"full_text":"\u00aeir inramsuflk HemlD\nEstablished July 4, 1892\nEntered as second-class matter in the Postoffice\nBrownsville rexas\nTHE BROWNSVILLE HERALD PUBLISHING\nCOMPANY\nSubscription Bates\u2014Daily and Sunday (7 Issues)\nDne Year ...$9 00\nBiz Months\nThree Months.....12.25\nDne Month.75\nMEMBER OF TI1E ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press Is exclusively entitled to the use\nfor publication of all news dispatches credited to It or\nnot otherwise credited In this paper, and also the\nlocal news published herein.\nHarlingen Office. Reese-Wil-Mond Hotel. Phone 1020\nTEXAS DAILY PRi SS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDallas. Texas. 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City. Mo.. 306 Coca Cola Building.\nChicago. Ill, Association Building.\nNew York. 350 Madison Avenue.\nSt. Louis. 502 Star Building.\nLos Angeles. Cal.. Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg.\n846 8. Broadway.\nSan Francisco, Cal., 318 Kohl Building.\nLegge Never Sidesteps\nAlexander W. Legge is chairman of the federal farm\n>oard. He was bom on a farm. When old enough he\nmoved to town. In time he became the $100,000 a\nyear president of a vast corporation turning out\nfarm machinery and tools for the farm. He was\ndrafted for the place he holds. He gave up the $100,\n000 Job for a $12,000 job, promising to serve a year.\nHe finds arrayed against him Julius Barnes, an\nImportant spokesman of the national chamber of\ncommerce and the big voice of grain corporations\nand grain exchanges.\nBarnes is close to Hoover. At one time they were\nJoint owners in a Washington newspaper. They\nwere buddies in the work of distributing American\nbread to the Belgian children.\nBarnes demands the scalp of Legge. All the big\ngrain exchange men are against Legge. All the big\nelevator men are against Legge. All the big cotton\nbuyers are against Legge.\nLegge knows it. He doesn't mind it. His latest is\nthat salvation for the American farmer lies in a col\nlective attitude towards cooperative organizations to\nitabilize prices.\nMoreover he says the weakness of the cooperative\ntoday is that it has not gone far enough.\nContacts with the terminal markets must be made\nfor the reason that every well organized industry ad\njusts its production to the demand Is the argument\nof this farm-bom president on the federal relief\nboard.\nAs for the farmer. to Legge. he does\nnot adjust production to the demand. He fails, and\nwhen prices are low. he raises more in order to tide\nhim over until he can make more money.\nThen what happens? Why low price commodity\nhas an Increased production and down goes the price\nagain.\nAlexander W. Legge is opposed to large scale farm\ning. through the plan of placing several thousands\nof acres under one management. These are his\nwords:\n\"I THINK IT IS A MISTAKE TO STRIKE AT\nIHE INDIVIDUAL FARM. THIS GREAT AMERI\nCAN INSTITUTION IS THE BULWARK OF THE\nVATION.\u2019\u2019\nBut back to Julius Barnes and the powerful indi\nviduals and organizations behind him. In the coming\nmonth of June or July Alexander W. Legge will have\nserved his term of one year.\nWill President Hoover redraft him or will Julius\nBarnes get the scalp of the farm boy who became the\n$100,000 a year president of the corporation that nip\nplies the farmer with machinery and tools?\nLegge Defends Mexican Labor\nAlexander W. Legge appeared before the house\nImmigration committee and advised the national law\nmakers to investigate carefully before approving any\nbill that would deprive the agricultural southwest of\nMexican labor. He warned the committee if Mexican\nlabor were made unavailable to truck and fruit farm\ning. \"the land will probably be devoted to cereals, of\nwhich the country now produces a very great excess\nand on which we are putting forth our best effort\nto try to curtail the acreage.\u201d\nBox fired a volley of questions at the chairman of\nthe federal farm board. Box contended that the big\nland owners are asking for a continuous flow of\nMexican labor for the reason that the land owners\nwant Mexicans \"to grub new land to be planted In\ncotton and to help cultivate and gather the cotton\ncrop.\"\nThis brought the information from Chairman Leggc\nthat he was only recommending the admission of sea\nsoned laborers for some sections of the extreme south\nwest, and he very bluntly stated that cotton acre\nage would have to be curtailed If that crop was to be\nplaced on a profitable basis.\nOf course, the free farmers of Texas who grow\ncotton are compelled to face the competition of con\nvicts on the 90.000 acres of prison land and the con\nvicts are said to be housed and fed and clothed by\nthe tax payers of the state of Texas.\nIf the Mexican Is a competitor of the Texas cot\nton grower, Is he a greater menace than the cor.vlct\nemployed in the growing of cotton by the law makers\nof the commonwealth?\n-1\nThe Once Over\nBy a L PHILLIPS\nELMER TWITCHELL ON PRESIDENTIAL\nANGLING\n(Copyright, 1930. by The Associated Newspapers.)\nElmer Twitchell isn't impressed by President Hoo\nver's fishing prowess as pictured in the newspaper\ndispatches. Elmer thinks it's all done by mirrors.\n\n\u201cYou noticed that when Mr. Hoover caught all\nthose big fish.\" said Mr. Twitchell, \u201che was accom\npanied by close associates and stalwart Republicans.\nI'll believe he* caught a 45-pound sailflsh when I\nhear there was some democrats and strangers in\nthe boat.\n\nWhen Mr. Hoover goes fishing he is accompanied\nby his secretary, his i>ersonal physician, his favorite\nnewspaper corretpondent and his great friend, Jus\ntice Harlan Stone\u201d continued Elmer.\u201d You never\nhear of him letting anybody like Senator Walsh of\nMontana in the boat, do you? Not much!\n\n\u201cPersonally I've got a hunch that Herbert Hoover\nain't so hot about fishing, anyhow. I think he really\ndislikes it and that the Republican party is jus:\nbuilding up a Hoover fisherworm myth.\n\n\u201cIt's a well known fact that the first thing a party\ntries to do with a new President is to get him into\nthe public mind as a sportsman of some kind or an\nother. It helps to popularize him and make him\nmore human. Now Mr. Hoover don t hunt, he ain t\na dashing horseman and he didn't play golf. Those\nstories about his morning handball games didn't get\nacross big, so they decided to make him a fisher\nman.\n\n\u201cThe public always warms up to a man who goes\nfishing. Look how it worked with Calvin Coolidge.\nCal was about the most colorless President the G\nO. P. ever had on its hands. It knew it never could\nput him across as a lion-hunter, a great athlete or a\nman who got 300 yards with his wooden clubs, so\nit made him a fisherman and got away with It.\n\n\u201cIf any man ever suffered when fishing it was\nCalvin Coolidge and I think that was one reason\nhe refused to run again. If the party h; d agreed to\nlet him bum his tackle he would have consented to\nrenomination.\n\n\u201cIt\u2019s the same game all over again with Hoover.\nThe G. O. P. is determined to put him over as a\nmighty fisherman, the Florida Chambers of Com\nmerce cooperating to the limit.\u201d\n\n\u201cNo sir,\" concluded Elmer, \u201cI'm not being fooled.\nIf the Republican party wants to convince me that\nHerbert Hoover dashes to the Florida keys, rushes\nout in a boat and spins back in no time with a 45\npound sailfish. let it send him out in a boat with\nAl Smith or Mr. Raskob or somebody like that.\u201d\nFOOD FOR THE JOKESMITHS\nThe Smithsonian Institution has grown a tomato\nwithout the use of dirt. It is to be hoped it will\nget busy at once with spinach and strawberries.\n______\nThe Fascisti administration in Italy has forbidden\nall jokes about the order. This is a certain sign it\nmust be getting pretty weak.\nTHE OLD HOME TOWN.- Stanley\nf f Cm\nMARSHAL- OTEY WALKER. CERTAiNLY HAD\nSOMETHING IN MINa^HEN HE 8cei^OWED\n\"THAT LITTLE BOYS SLED-JUST TO SEE\nHOW CLOSE HE COULD COME TO THIS\nSTRANGER. WITHOUT H)T77NCH)M\ntMOiee DETAJUS (N 7UMORR3WS PAO\u00a3^\n^1510 tC\u00ab tTMLtY CCNT\u00bbA^ PUg-A^ a-ie-IO\nCHAPTER 47\nOn the following day, Tuesday,\nPat and her friends and the yacht's\nowner, Howard Wlckly, met at the\noffice of Marks, the lawyer, where a\nbill of sale was drawn up. signed and\ngiven Pat in exchange for her certi\nfied check for $150,000. She was also\npresented with the vessel\u2019s insurance\npapers. It was decided that after\nnoon that on the following Monday,\nat noon, the party should be aboard\nthe BLUEBIRD ready for the start\nthe Bermudas beiny nanrd as the\nfirst destination.\nThat same evening Lucy Pine ar\nrived at the Lynne home in a per\nfect frenzy of excitement over the\nprospective yachting cruise. It was\nin the course of the conversation\nthat evening that Pat came to know\nsomething of the difficulties Dr.\nPine had to meet in the conduct of\nhis sanitarium. Fully a third of his\npatients, Pat learned were the non\npaying kind. But they received the\nsame treatment, Lucy declared, that\nwas given thoee who paid. She had\nnever known her father, she said,\nto turn away one in need.\nIt was through Lucy and her\nfather, Pat reminded herself, that\nJimmy had been restored to her. To\nthis remembrance was owing a fold\ned slip that Pat placed in Lucy's\nhandbag the next afternoon as the\ndoctor s daughter was starting back\nhome to remain until Sunday, when\nshe was rejoin her friends to go\naboard the yacht. Lucy was to give\nthe slip to her father, Pat told her.\nAlter the girl had climbed into her\nflivver coupe and was on her way\nback to Yonkers, she bethought her\nself of the slip and opened her hand\nbag to look at it. That which she\nsaw caused her, almost, to run her\ncar into the corner fruit stand. It\nwas a check for $10,000. made pay\nable to Dr. Pine and signed by Pa\ntricia Blair.\nThe darling girl!\" w'hlspered Lucy\nwith a quick little sob of Joy at the\nthought of how happy it would make\nher harrassed old father, whose in\ncome for several years had been\ni stretched to its lull limit. Ten thous\nand dollars! It would certainly re\ncompense him for the loss of her\nservices during the yachting cruise.\nThe sending of that check was des\ntined alsa to prove in a most satis\nfactory way. the truth once more\nof the old saying about \"bread cast\nupon tha waters returning alter j\nmany Cays.\u201d\nTire next day after Lucy\u2019s visit\nwas given over to a general shop- j\nping expedition by the entire party, i\nduring which, the girls and Aunt\n__\nJ j\nI Grab Bag t\nWho am I? What Is my position?\nWho Is the U. S. representative to\nmy country?\nWho was the first Englishman to\ncircumnavigate the globe?\n\nWhat was the real name of John\nny Appleseed?\n\"A new commandment I give\nunto you, That ye love one an\nother; as I have loved you. that\nye also love one another\" Where\nis this passage found in the Bible?\nCorrectly Speaking\u2014\nStatements which are permanent\nly true should always be put in the\npresent tense. For example, \"He\nsaid diamonds are precious stones.\"\nis correct and \"He said diamonds\nwere precious stones\" is incorrect.\nToday\u2019s Anniversary\nOn this ray. in 1795. George Pea\nbody. the American philanthropist,\nwas born.\nToday\u2019s Horoscope\nPersons born on this day are\nthrifty and look out for a rainy\nday.\nAnswers to Foregoing Questions\n1. Herr F. W. von Prittwltz und\nGaffron; German ambassador to\nthe United States; Frederic M.\nSackett.\n2. Sir Francis Drake.\n3. John Chapman.\n4. St. John, xili, 34.\n1 Star Lore]\nWHY A \u201cPERPETUAL MOTION\"\nSTOPS MOVING\nBy Arthur DeV. Carpenter\nThe earth, in its mighty orbit\naround the sun, is a perpetual mo\ntion; it meets with no resistance\nin its onward rush. But every at\ntempt of man to produce a per\npetual motion meets with that\nirresistible influence known a\nfriction. No artificial vacuum is a\nperfect vacuum. No physical move\nment can be set up that does not\ninstantaneously meet with resist\nance. both from the atmosphere\nand from gravitation, that will\nultimately bring it to a standstill.\nYears ago the writer saw \"a per\npetual motion\" resembling a scenic\nrailway. The ball went on its way\ntill it came to the critical place\nwhere it received a kick from an\ninconspicuous spring.\n'**ore Tomorrow)\nLottie not only fitted themselves out\nfor the coming yachting trip, but\nJimmy as well. With the help of Rex\nand Frank. Jimmy was fitted with\nseveral suits, including white flan\nnels. and everything in the line of\nwearing apparel.\nOn Monday at 11:00 a. m.. they\nwent aboard. The steward had been\ngiven instructions to purchase every\nthing that might add to the comfort\nand pleasure of everybody for a six\nmonth's cruise. The luncheon that\nwas served at one o'clock by the\ntwo waiters while the yacht still re\nmained at her dock, was a very sat\nisfying evidence of both the ste\nward's and the chef\u2019s qualifications.\nIt was while they were getting\naway from the dock that Margery\nnoticed one of the three new deck\nhands. Pat and she, with Rex and\nthe doctor, were standing in the big,\nroomy pilot house, where the cap\ntain, who was at the wheel, had in\nvited them.\n\u201cThat man's face is very familiar\nto me.\" she said to everybody in\ngereral and indicating the man re\nferred to, who, at that moment, was\njust lifting the noose of the forward\nline over the top of the pile. \"I've\nseen him somewhere, I'm positive,\"\nshe went on. ruminatively, \u201cbut I\ncan't quite place him!\"\n\u201cWell. I hardly think he'll ever\nbe picked as the winner of any\nbeauty contest,\u201d opined Rex, favor\ning the man with a contemplative\nlook. \"For I don't just admire the\ncut of his jib,\u2019 to use a sailor\u2019s\nphrase.\"\n\u201cI don't know his name,\" said\nCaptain Lee from his stand in front\nof the wheel, where he had just\npressed a brass knob, signalling the\nengine room. \u201cHe is one of the three\nnew deck hands Mister Paulson, the\nsecond officer, hired Saturday.**\n\u201cHe has a vicious looking mouth.\u201d\nobserved Pat, who very rarely spoke\nin the least way derogatory of any\nperson. \u201cI would imagine he had an\nungovernable temper,\u201d she added af\nter another glance at the fellow who.\nat that instant was approaching\nthe yacht's rail, the loop of the\nheavy rope hanging lrom his should\nA trifling incident, apparently.\nAnd yet, as every person knows, it\nis frequently the trifling incident\nthat points the way, almost direct\nly, to the overwhelming disaster,\nor the astonishing good fortune.\nHad Margery's memory during\nthose few moments in the pilot\nhouse, had she recalled the oc\ncasion upon which she had seen\nthat man\u2019s face, that recollection\nwould, in all probability, have al\ntered materially the outcome of this\nstory.\nThe man certainly would not, as\nRex had said, ever be picked as a\nbeauty prize winner. His brick-red\nhair, coarse and wiry, seemed to\ngrow straight out lrotn the scalp.\nHis scrub-brush of a moustache\nand the heavy beetling eyebrows\nlent a fierce aspect to the face, a\nlook that ni accentuated by the\nsmall, pig-hke eyes. In build he was\nshort and squat, his small head\nthe appearance of a monstrous pim\nple growing out between the wide\nshoulders.\n\u201cWhat's the best time the Blue\nbird will make under good condi\ntions, Captain?\" asked Rex, as the\nslight vibration told of the propel\nler's start, the craft beginning to\nforge slowly ahead.\nCaptain Lee made no Immediate\nreply. His gaze was fixed on the\nnarrow space between his ship\u2019s\nport rail and the huge abutments\nof the dock along the side of which,\nthe yacht was now gliding with a\nswiftly increasing speed. A moment\nlater the dock\u2019s end slipped past\nthe line of vision in the pilot house\nand the vessel was heading out in\nto the open Hudson. Then the cap\ntain turned toward his questioner.\nHis wmd-blown eyes twinkled the\ncomers of his mouth.\n\u201cYou'd be like to thinkin' I was\na liar.\" he said in his throaty\ndrawling tones, \u201cif I told you hon\nestly what I've done with this shipl\nOld sailormen of the windjammer\ndays always tell me I\u2019m crazy when\nI mention her best running time!\"\n\u201cNo. no. I'll believe you, Captain!\u201c\navowed Rex with quick eagerness.\n\u201cGo ahead. Give us the low-down\non her speed qualities!\"\n\"Well, sir.\u201d began the old navigat\nor as he turned the small electrical\nly-controlled wheel a few inches to\nport, glanced carefully ahead and\nthen looked sideways at Dallard.\n\u201cI've stood at this wheel here for\nan hour at a time when this vessel\nwas a-traveling through the wat\u00ab\nat a thirty knot clip! Yes, sir!\n\"For you understand,\" went on\nthe captain with the true pride in\nhis own ship's abilities. \u201cThe Blue\nbird has the latest improved model\nturbine engines and two four\nbucket propellers that are bigger\nthan many liner's! You can't feel\na particle of vibration now at ten\nmiles an hour. Even at thirty, it's\nonly a little noticeable. That's be\ncause of her steel keelson and the\nway she's reinforced forward and\naft. She's built for speed, and\nproperly handled, she\u2019ll nose into\nany sea that ever rolled.\u201d\n\u201cOne would say that Captain Lee\nSAMBO\u2019S PHILOSOPHY\n-\u25a0fcome u.ik>-es git nauea \\wut>\nTHUS\u2019ASM, an' a Leap uio\u2019 fer d\u00ab\nLACK o\u2019 LU.\u201d\nANOTHER CHICAGO \u201cLOOP\u201d I\nthinks pretty well of the Bluebird!\"\nwas Dallard's comment a few min\nutes later as the four made their\nway aft the officers\u2019 deck down to\nthe main cabin. \"At that,\u201d he add\ned half musingly, \"I reckon he has\ngood reason for his belief in her!\"\nThey had left Jimmy seated in\na deep, upholstered chair with\nLucy Pine and Aunt Lottie look-.\ning after him. He was still sitting\nthere. He certainly was one young\ngentleman, as Margery so aptly\nphrased it. who. when put in his\nproper place, \"stayed put!\"\n(TO BE CONTINUED)\nReal Estate Board\nTo Visit in Valley\n(Special to The Herald)\nMcALLEN, Feb. 18\u2014A group of\n50 to 100 members of the farm\nlands division of the National As\nsociation of Real Estate Boards\nwill visit some city in the Lower\nRio Grande Valley, yet to be select\ned. in April following a meeting of\nmembers of that division in Tex\nas, according to information re\nceived by the McAllen Real Estate\nboard.\nThree McAllen realtors. D. W.\nRowe, Paul W. Barron and A. A.\nHughes, have been named as a\ncommittee to complete arrange\nments for the visit of the national\nrealtors.\nThe invitation to visit the Val\nley was extended to the farm lands\ndivision by George W. Huffman of\nHouston, secretary of the division.\n51 Business Firms\nFight Hot Checks\n(Special to The Herald)\nMcALLEN. Feb. 18\u2014A totil of 51\nbusiness firms of McAllen have an\nnounced their intention of backing\na concerted fight being waged by\nValley retail merchants' associations\nTANLAC ENDS\nANOTHER CASE OF\nRHEUMATISM\nand Stomach Troubles\u2014Hotol\nMan Benefits This Tima\nEnding the suffering of 10 years\nin just a few weeks is going some\nbut that\u2019s just an example of how\nquickly Tanlac works in stubborn\ncases that never yield to other\nremedies.\nNo wonder e\u00a9 many local people are eo\nenthusiastic about Tanlac\u2014no wonder lo\ncal druggists are loud in praiae of this\nmedicine. Read for instance what Mr. J.\nL.. Kline aay\u00bb: \"For 10 years have bad\netomach troubles. Rheumatism also of\nmorning*, stiff and sore all over, mostly\nin back and rhoulders. A good powerful\nmedicine was needed to fi* me up and\nTanlac proved to be all of that. From it 1\ngit relief from all trouble*, ctomaeb\nand rheumatism. My digestion now i* just\nabout lOO^e good. No more pain or dis\ntress. eat good, sleep as good as I eat.\npain, stiffness, soreness all gone. Rheuma\ntism in hark and shoulders wiped out. I\nhave tried out lots of medicines but Tan\nlac gave me results.\u201d Tbat\u2019e the etory of\nTanlac in a nutshell\u2014it give* results and\ngives them quick, for every herb, bark\ni and root is a real medicine. Many \u201cpatent\nmedicines\" make glowing promises that\n1 may fool you into buying them, but re\nmember Tanlac is a real medicine that\nbacks its claims with a guarantee. At all\ndruggists. Accept no substitute.\nJ ATTENTION! j\nf We have added a j\nRental Library to our I\nIt store! Come in and look\nI it over. All of the best X\nsellers of all publishers. X\nKeep abreast of the f\nmost popular new books\nIt by renting them at i\nX small cost!\nI HARGROVE\u2019S I\nI Stationery Book Store J\nL Phone 348\nBrownsville, Texas\nagainst \u201chot check\" writers in this!\nsection.\nA petition was being circulated\nSaturday among McAllen mer\nchants which bound each signer\nto file a complaint against proven\nwriters of \u201chot\" checks and con\ntinue the prosecution of the case\nto the fullest extent of the law.\nA number of Lower Rio Grande\nValley communities have combined\nin an effort to rid this South Tex\nas section of a nuisance said to\nbe costing merchants of the ter\nritory thousands of dollars annual\nly. _\nMADRID UP)\u2014Although virtually\nall talkies shown here are in Eng\nlish. movie houses report a boom\ning business. Patrons are clamoring,\nhowever, for films in Spanish.\nEat At\nAnthony\u2019s Waffle\nShop\n517 12 St Phone 983\nA. TAMM\nBlue Printing and\nSupplies\nHarlingen, Texas\n1911 1930\nSkelton Abstract Co.\nAbstracts of Title \"Title Insurance\nMerchants Bank Building Brownsville\nI\nProsperity for Brownsville and\nthe Valley is a tangible, able-to\nbe-seen condition. Citrus grove.4*\nire beginning to bloom vege*\nables are commanding good\nprices generally the interna\nional airport and the brighi\nprospects for a deep water port\u2014\nall are encouraging a splendid\nbusiness outlook for Brownsville\nand the Valley.\nLet us. as your bank, help\nyou with any problems you\nmay wish to discuss with us.\nFirst National Bank\nEstablished in 1891\nBROWNSVILLE, TEXAS\n_t","height":"36356","width":"27448"}}
